==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*kwēni-'', from Indo-European ''*gʷenh₂-''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[quan|quān]], Old Norse [[kvæn]], Gothic [[𐌵𐌴𐌽𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[γυνη]], Slavic ''*ženā'' (Old Church Slavonic [[жена]], Russian [[жена]]), Old Irish [[ben]] (Welsh [[benyw]]), Albanian [[zonjë]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /kwe:n/

===Noun===
'''cwēn''' ''f'' (''pl'' '''cwēna''' or '''cwēne''')
# a [[woman]]
#:''Seo clæneste cwen ofer eorþan'': the purest woman on earth.
# a [[wife]]
# a [[queen]]
#:''Aðelwulf cyng Carles dohtor hæfde to cwene'': King Athelwulf took Charles's daughter as his queen.

